  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices date back to the 1920s\n- Initial efforts focused on combating organized crime revenue during Prohibition era\n\n2. Initial Formal Legislation\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970 (United States)\n- First comprehensive legal framework requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting requirements to detect potential criminal financial activities\n\n3. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n- Created global framework for AML regulations\n\n4. Significant Expansion\n- 1990s: More comprehensive international and national AML laws\n- United States' Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Expanded criminal penalties and reporting requirements\n- Introduced specific money laundering as a distinct federal crime\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments\n- Patriot Act of 2001 significantly enhanced AML and counter-terrorism financing regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Strengthened international cooperation mechanisms\n\n6. Ongoing Global Regulatory Evolution\n- Continuous refinement of legal frameworks\n- Increased focus on digital currency and emerging financial technologies",
